[ProMED-mail is indebted to Jacqueline Weyer and colleagues for
providing this update on the progress of the current outbreak of Rift
Valley fever in South Africa. Previous reports indicated that the
outbreak was confined to the Free State, but human cases have been
recorded now in Eastern Cape and Northern Cape provinces. In addition
animal cases have been recorded in Gauteng and Mpumalanga provinces
and human cases may follow.

Outbreaks of Rift Valley fever are associated characteristically with
persistent heavy rainfall with sustained flooding and the appearance
of large numbers of mosquitoes, the main vector. Localised heavy
rainfall is seldom sufficient to create conditions for an outbreak;
the simultaneous emergence of large numbers of 1st generation
transovarially infected mosquitoes is also required. After virus
amplification in vertebrates, mosquitoes act as secondary vectors to
sustain the epidemic.

Genome analysis has confirmed that this outbreak is associated with
one of the 2 strains of Rift valley fever virus that have emerged
locally in South Africa in recent years. According to Bird et al.
(Journal of Virology, 2007 Mar;81(6):2805-16) Rift Valley fever virus
strains isolated within an epidemic have exhibited little diversity,
whereas those in enzootic settings can be highly diverse. Virus
genetic diversity within epidemics was low (approximately 5 percent)
and primarily involved accumulation of mutations at an average of 2.9
x 10(-4) substitutions/site/year, and with some evidence of sub-unit
reassortment.

Interestingly their Bayesian analysis of Rift Valley fever virus
genetic diversity placed the most recent common ancestor of these
viruses in the late 1800s, the colonial period in Africa, a time of
dramatic changes in agricultural practices and introduction of
nonindigenous livestock breeds.

A map of the provinces of South Africa can be accessed at:
<http://www.sa-venues.com/maps/south-africa-provinces.htm>.
The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of South Africa is available at:
<http://healthmap.org/r/00vd>.
- Mod.CP]
